**Karyn Parsons** (born October 8, 1966)[1] is an American actress and
comedian. She is best known for her role as [Hilary Banks](/wiki/Hilary_Banks
"Hilary Banks") on the [NBC](/wiki/NBC "NBC") [sitcom](/wiki/Sitcom "Sitcom")
_[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air](/wiki/The_Fresh_Prince_of_Bel-Air "The Fresh
Prince of Bel-Air")_ from 1990–1996. Parsons also starred in the 1995 film
_[Major Payne](/wiki/Major_Payne "Major Payne")_ opposite [Damon
Wayans](/wiki/Damon_Wayans "Damon Wayans").

## Early
life[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Karyn_Parsons&action=edit&section=1&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Early life")]

Parsons was born in [Los Angeles](/wiki/Los_Angeles "Los Angeles"),
[California](/wiki/California "California"). In an interview for
_[Essence](/wiki/Essence_\(magazine\) "Essence \(magazine\)")_ in 2008, she
described her parentage as biracial.[2] Her mother, Louise Parsons, is an
African American from [Charleston, South
Carolina](/wiki/Charleston,_South_Carolina "Charleston, South Carolina") and
her father, Kenneth B. Parsons, is of [Welsh](/wiki/Welsh_people "Welsh
people") descent and from [Butte, Montana](/wiki/Butte,_Montana "Butte,
Montana"). She attended [Santa Monica High
School](/wiki/Santa_Monica_High_School "Santa Monica High School").[3]

##
Career[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Karyn_Parsons&action=edit&section=2&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Career")]

Parsons starred as [Hilary Banks](/wiki/Hilary_Banks "Hilary Banks") on the
sitcom _[The Fresh Prince of Bel-Air](/wiki/The_Fresh_Prince_of_Bel-Air "The
Fresh Prince of Bel-Air")_ , which aired on [NBC](/wiki/NBC "NBC") from 1990
to 1996. She co-created, co-produced, co-wrote, and co-starred on the
[Fox](/wiki/Fox_Broadcasting_Company "Fox Broadcasting Company") sitcom _[Lush
Life](/wiki/Lush_Life_\(TV_series\) "Lush Life \(TV series\)")_ in 1996, which
was later canceled after four episodes. In 2001, she starred in the critically
acclaimed but short-lived television series _[The
Job](/wiki/The_Job_\(2001_TV_series\) "The Job \(2001 TV series\)")_ with
[Denis Leary](/wiki/Denis_Leary "Denis Leary"). Besides television, Parsons
has starred in several films, particularly in comedies such as _Late Nights_
(1992), _[Major Payne](/wiki/Major_Payne "Major Payne")_ (1995), and _[The
Ladies Man](/wiki/The_Ladies_Man_\(2000_film\) "The Ladies Man \(2000
film\)")_ (2000). Parsons is the creator of Sweet Blackberry, a line of
animated films about unsung black heroes. The first in the series is about
[Henry "Box" Brown](/wiki/Henry_%22Box%22_Brown "Henry "Box" Brown"), a
[slave](/wiki/Slavery "Slavery") who mailed himself to freedom.[4]

## Personal
life[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Karyn_Parsons&action=edit&section=3&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro
"Edit section: Personal life")]

Parsons married _[The Young and the Restless](/wiki/The_Young_and_the_Restless
"The Young and the Restless")_ actor [Randy
Brooks](/wiki/Randy_Brooks_\(actor\) "Randy Brooks \(actor\)") in 1987; they
divorced in 1990.[_[citation needed](/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed
"Wikipedia:Citation needed")_] Parsons married director [Alexandre
Rockwell](/wiki/Alexandre_Rockwell "Alexandre Rockwell") in 2003. Together
they have a daughter, Lana (born June 8, 2003), and a son, Nico (born April
11, 2007).[5]
